  <!-- Executive Summary -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Executive Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The FDA's Bioresearch Monitoring (BIMO) program has intensified its scrutiny of clinical
      investigator conduct over the last 24 months. Publicly available BIMO inspection metrics
      and secondary compliance analyses consistently show that a meaningful share of US clinical
      sites that get inspected receive observations, with protocol non-compliance cited as the
      leading issue in recent BIMO warning letters<sup><a href="#cite-1">1</a></sup>. Three
      illustrative cases below extract recurring failure modes relevant to oncology sites,
      each drawn from a verified warning letter currently live on FDA.gov:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Dosing past confirmed disease progression</strong> — the most public 2024–2025 oncology enforcement signal</li>
      <li><strong>Genetic / biomarker sub-study consent failures</strong> — a consent failure mode that appears uniquely in targeted oncology protocols</li>
      <li><strong>Investigational product accountability breakdowns</strong> — protocol misinterpretation leading to unplanned additional dosing in pediatric oncology</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Each failure concentrates operational risk at the site level, not the sponsor level — meaning
      most oncology sponsors cannot mitigate the exposure through remote monitoring alone.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Finding 1 -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Case 1 — Dosing past confirmed progression (2025 enforcement signal)</h2>
    <p>
      In September 2025, the FDA issued warning letter <strong>716181-09042025</strong> to Dr. Shirish M. Gadgeel,
      a thoracic oncologist at Henry Ford Health, following an August 5–23, 2024 BIMO inspection<sup><a href="#cite-2">2</a></sup>.
      The letter cites progression per modified RECIST 1.1, documented per tumor measurement reports of
      <strong>September 16, 2021 and November 9, 2021</strong>. The protocol required removal from treatment once progression was met.
    </p>
    <p>
      Despite that, the subject received IV infusions of the investigational drug on October 12 and November 9, 2021 —
      with sponsor approval for continued dosing not obtained until <strong>November 23, 2021</strong>,
      after dosing had already occurred. The subject was not formally removed from study treatment until
      January 3, 2022, more than three months after progression was documented. The letter cites failure
      to comply with 21 CFR 312.60.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Why this compounds in 2025–2026:</strong> as targeted oncology protocols embed hard RECIST-based stopping
      rules, sites running multiple investigational oncology protocols simultaneously must implement
      per-protocol stop-rule operational workflows — not rely on physician memory. FDA's December 30, 2024 draft guidance
      on Protocol Deviations<sup><a href="#cite-3">3</a></sup> signals increased inspection focus on this
      category in 2026.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Finding 2 -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Case 2 — Genetic / biomarker sub-study consent failures</h2>
    <p>
      The same Gadgeel warning letter cites a second distinct failure. The IRB-approved protocol required
      subjects to sign a <em>separate special consent</em> for inherited genetic analysis before blood samples
      could be collected for that purpose. No separate consent was obtained for a subject whose blood was drawn
      for genetic analysis at <strong>Cycle 2, Day 1 (May 25, 2021) and Cycle 3, Day 1 (June 15, 2021)</strong><sup><a href="#cite-2">2</a></sup>.
      The letter cites 21 CFR 50.20 — failure to obtain legally effective informed consent.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Why this is oncology-specific:</strong> targeted oncology protocols increasingly nest optional
      genetic profiling, circulating tumor DNA collection, and biomarker sub-studies inside the main consent.
      Sites that treat the master consent as covering all components face direct 21 CFR 50.20 / 50.25 exposure
      when a protocol-required separate consent is not obtained. The operational risk concentrates at the coordinator
      level — per-sample consent verification must live in the sample collection workflow, not just at enrollment.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Finding 3 -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Case 3 — Investigational product accountability (pediatric oncology)</h2>
    <p>
      Warning letter <strong>674545-12192023</strong>, issued to Dr. Jeffrey W. Taub (Chief, Pediatric
      Hematology-Oncology, Children's Hospital of Michigan), documents a different failure mode following a
      <strong>September 23 – October 12, 2022</strong> BIMO inspection<sup><a href="#cite-4">4</a></sup>.
      A pediatric subject received <strong>three additional five-day cycles of vincristine and dexamethasone
      at Weeks 53, 57, and 61</strong> — beyond the schedule the protocol specified. Root cause: a physician
      subinvestigator misinterpreted the drug administration plan. FDA specifically noted that pediatric subjects
      administered vincristine are exposed to serious neurologic and hematologic toxicity, amplifying the clinical risk of excess dosing.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hospital's corrective action plan was found inadequate.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Why this matters for oncology sites specifically:</strong> protocol schedule misinterpretation is
      a quiet failure mode — it does not register as non-compliance until FDA reconstructs the expected vs. actual
      dosing timeline. For oncology protocols with complex dose-escalation, induction-consolidation-maintenance
      phases, or cycle-based schedules, risk concentrates in the handoff between protocol reading and dose administration.
      Sites running cytotoxic or narrow-therapeutic-window oncology regimens should assume this failure mode applies
      unless a formal second-check workflow exists at the pharmacy and coordinator level.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Base Rate -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Base rate — how exposed are sites overall?</h2>
    <p>
      FDA publishes annual BIMO Inspection Metrics by fiscal year<sup><a href="#cite-5">5</a></sup>.
      In recent years, across BIMO inspections at US clinical sites, the classification distribution has been
      approximately as follows:
    </p>
    <div class="compare-table-wrap">
      <table class="compare-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Outcome</th>
            <th scope="col">Share</th>
            <th scope="col">What it means</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>NAI</strong> (No Action Indicated)</td>
            <td>~75–80%</td>
            <td>No objectionable conditions cited</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>VAI</strong> (Voluntary Action Indicated)</td>
            <td>~18–25%</td>
            <td>Observations issued; site responds in writing</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>OAI</strong> (Official Action Indicated)</td>
            <td>~1–2%</td>
            <td>Serious — may trigger warning letter or further enforcement</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      <strong>Translation:</strong> roughly 1 in 5 inspected US clinical sites receives observations (VAI),
      and about 1 in 50 escalate to serious action (OAI). Among the top-cited regulatory sections in recent warning letters:
      21 CFR 312.60 (investigational plan adherence), 21 CFR 312.20 (IND submission), 21 CFR 312.57 (record maintenance),
      and 21 CFR 50.25 (informed consent requirements)<sup><a href="#cite-6">6</a></sup>.
    </p>
  </section>

